description: From Middle English leesewe, lesewe, leswe, from Old English lǣs (“pasture”), from Proto-West Germanic *lāsu (“pasture”).

entries.meaning: (now rare, dialectal, historical) (Green) land as opposed to flood or desert; a pasture.
examples: Reflexions in her Book, strike one as a Statue does among the tangled Thickets of the Leasowes  […] .

verbs.description: leasow (third-person singular simple present leasows, present participle leasowing, simple past and past participle leasowed)

entries.meaning: (transitive, archaic or dialectal) To feed or pasture
